<HR size="1" color="#12350C">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
For being the masters of Mind control, I find that our Mind line is consistently restricted and continues to be so, most especially noticably in RvR.<P>The Mind line is the definitive characteristic of our class.  Sure, we can specialize fully in Body and Matter, but those specs just increase the base lines (a Body-Specced Sorcerer won't be caught dead using the power-draining Lifedrain spells instead of his Mind Blast line).  And even a Body Sorcerer can use his baseline Mind powers of Mezzing, Confusing, Amnesia, etc.<P>So why then are so few of our Mind powers utilized in RvR?<P>Confusion - Does not work at ALL in RvR.  Not even in any form!  Is it so incomprehensible to have it work on a DoT timer to make the foe change targets randomly?  Again, it's a strategical advantage, and might warrant being cast before a fight.  Then again, it isn't AE, so it wouldn't be grossly overpowering in a big conflict.  So what about one-on-one conflicts?  Well, confuse would be worthless then, wouldn't it, since there's no targets nearby to have the timer randomly click on to.<P>Debuffs - Not just the Mind ones, but all debuffs are continually being found worthless in RvR settings.  Are there noticable effects?  Is it worth casting?  Most Sorcerers tend to say no.  Battles last a very short amount of time, since so much damage is flying around and people end up very dead very fast, people find strategy is not as important as raw nuking power.  So when they choose between a debuff and a Mind Blast, they almost always choose the mind blast, again because debuffs provide us with no *genuine noticable effects*.  <P>Amnesia - It's a great idea, and might even make sense to cast in certain situations.  The range is the only benefit about it; in RvR all it does is interrupt the target.  Is this intended?  Is this what Amnesia is envisioned to do in realm combat, make the person stumble a little?  Puh-lease, I hardly think so.  It only makes *perfect* sense to at least cause the foe to lose their target (do you know how long it takes to move your hand back to the mouse and manually reclick the target?).  That alone is at tactical advantage.<P>Charm - The pets are powerful (well, not as powerful as Minstrel's now, but that's okay), however there are a LOT of issues with them.  First, we need more control over them.  It's quite a sign of mind-control impotence if we cannot make a Wizard Pet send out a fireball when we want it to.  It would be infinately more viable and strategic to be able to direct when a pet uses their particular special abilities (IE Magic, Healing, Buffing, Ranged) when we want them to.  Pets in RvR now seem worthless because everyone knows that killing the Sorcerer just immediately solves the pet.<P>The second issue about Pets is range.  They are currently not commandable at bolt range...why??  If we can see a target clear as day, why can we not tell the pet, "Go kill that one, there!"  Increase the range of pets dramatically.  If you couple that with the ability to have greater control over the pets' special abilities, you'll see the usage of special pets increase...you'll see Sorcerers standing with their pets on walls, telling the little goblin wizard when to throw that fireball out.  You'll see Sorcerers turn into reality the term "pocket cleric".  The Masters of Mind Control should indeed be able to fully control their unwilling minion, and the minions themselves should be able to use their special abilities the range they're intended, that being bolts at bolt range and arrows at arrow range.<P>Lastly, there's the normal issues with pets that (1) they die too fast for us, since we have NO way of recovering their life except the very normal, highly slow method of standing recovery and (2) there aren't an ample supply of them in the places we need them (Frontiers, high-level places, maybe even some dungeons).  First, I understand that they die too fast, and that's the way it is.  But, while I think it wouldn't make any sense to give us a healing ability to recover their life, I think it *does* make sense to be able to command the charmed pet to sit and recover health at the extended sitting rate.  And as for not enough mobs...well, I think we definately need more mobs, and more variety of mobs (presuming that we'll gain control over all their special abilities), so that a Sorcerer gets to choose what kind of pet they'll be wanting, whether they want a Wizard pet, a Healer, a Melee/Guard, etc.
</FONT>
